NOTES.741:
I tag for the Southwest Monarch Study and was  delighted to to see a tagged monarch clinging to a pine branch in the New York Botanical Garden where I was visiting. It was a cloudy, chilly 53° and the monarch was still cold.  It was a FEMALE  in excellent condition looking very new. It was 8:58 AM. 
GPS coordinates were     40 51'49"N   73 52'49"W   140ft elevation

NOTES.847:
I actually first saw this tagged Monarch Jan 8, 2018 in my gardens around my house.  He has been here ever since that day, every day faithfully.  This is the first day after laying on the ground and waiting for him to come to his favorite nectar plant, lavendar, that I was able to get close enough to get a clear picture of his tag.  I have been helping the monarch population for two years, recently letting about 17 free.  Our garden club has named this year "The year of the butterfly"
encouraging everyone one to plant at least two butterfly plants around their house.  We have seen a real increase of their population.
